o -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGender discrimination pervades nearly all legal institutions and practices in Latin America. The deeper question is how this shapes broader relations of power. By examining the relationship between law and gender as it manifests itself in the Mexican legal system, the thirteen essays in this volume show how law is produced by, but also perpetuates, unequal power relations. At the same time, however, authors show how law is often malleable and can provide spaces for negotiation and redress. The contributors (including political scientists, sociologists, geographers, anthropologists, and economists) explore these issues-not only in courts, police stations, and prisons, but also in rural organizations, indigenous communities, and families. By bringing new interdisciplinary perspectives to issues such as the quality of citizenship and the rule of law in present-day Mexico, this book raises important issues for research on the relationship between law and gender more widely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aIndians of MexicoxLegal status, laws, etcxMexico. 0aIndians of Mexico. 0aSex and lawxLegal status, laws, etc.zMexico. 0aSex and lawxMexico. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etcxMexico. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zMexico. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAlonso, Ana M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlonso, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaitenmann, Helga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaitenmann, Helga, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChenaut, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l